caption: b'Always transforming. \n\n"Don\'t hesitate to learn (new technology) even if you\'re uncomfortable, because in this day and age, that\'s what everything is going to." - Matt Hernandez, INVISTA\'s fixed equipment inspector, who took an opportunity to become an FAA-certified drone pilot. Learning this technology not only transformed his role but led to safer and more efficient operations. Link in bio.'

b'#GivingTuesday. \n\nFor over 30 years, we\'ve supported our local Wichita Salvation Army (@salarmyict) through their annual Angel Tree campaign, supporting more than 1,000 Angels each year. b"What are you grateful for?

This Thanksgiving, we're dishing up an extra helping of gratitude for our employees. We were curious to hear what they're thankful for \xe2\x80\x93 so we asked them. Here are some of their responses.

Let us know what you're grateful for in the comments below."

b'Deck the halls (with boxes). 

Just like Santa, our team at @georgiapacific has a workshop of their own, where scientists (a.k.a box elves) discover packaging solutions for retailers and online retailers.

Much like the art of regifting, GP is focused on giving old boxes new life through recycling. Every year, GP collects approximately 5 million tons of recovered paper products, or about 250,000 truckloads, from large retailers, grocery stores and residences for recycling. Link in bio.'

b"Experimentation makes our world go round. \n\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s why we open our doors to collaborators to try out new things with our companies. We call it Koch Labs - and it's part of our business philosophy of Principled Entrepreneurship."

b'For entrepreneurs, failure often comes with the territory. \n\nEntrepreneur Brad Feld believes the ability to deal with failure in a realistic and healthy way, and to experiment, is key to a long-term successful entrepreneurial journey.  Link in bio. #gew2020 #globalentrepreneurshipweek #entrepreneurlife #entrepreneur #entrepreneurship'

b'Grit, tenacity and a good idea.\n\nThis and other pieces of advice for prospective entrepreneurs from Christina Long, president and CEO of Create Campaign, an organization that brings guidance, support and resources to entrepreneurs in Wichita\xe2\x80\x99s minority communities. More in bio. #gew2020 #globalentrepreneurshipweek #entrepreneurlife #entrepreneur'

b'United in gratitude. \n\nIn celebration of Veterans Day, we send our gratitude to the members of the U.S. armed forces, whether veteran or active duty. b'Ever wonder what Charles Koch wants for his birthday? We asked him.

\xe2\x80\x9cPeace, harmony, equal rights and mutual benefit where everyone had the opportunity to realize their potential.\xe2\x80\x9d

b'Happy Halloween from our 65,000 employees across America!'

b'Enhancing safety. Reducing emissions. \n\nAt Flint Hills Resources in Corpus Christi, one constant challenge is monitoring 250,000 hardware components for issues. Technicians walk around our refineries manually monitoring for leaks. But our teams at Flint Hills Resources and @MolexConnectors found a better way. They created a giant network of hundreds of sensors that could detect issues automatically and in real time \xe2\x80\x93 helping enhance safety and reduce emissions. Read more - link in bio.'

b'Finding potential early. 

Charles Koch and Chase Koch field questions from our summer intern class. See what advice the two had to offer about entering today\xe2\x80\x99s job market, transforming with technology and pursuing careers that provide fulfillment. 

\xe2\x80\x9cMy advice is to be the best \xe2\x80\x98you\xe2\x80\x99 you can be. Don\xe2\x80\x99t try to be something you\xe2\x80\x99re not. Don\xe2\x80\x99t go after shiny objects; find something that fits your gifts and your nature. Because, as Abraham Maslow said, \xe2\x80\x98What you can be, you must be.\xe2\x80\x99 If you evade your capacities and your potential, you will be unhappy the rest of your life.\xe2\x80\x9d - Charles Koch, on his advice for young adults entering the workforce today. Link bio for more. #nationalmentoringday  #nationalmentoringday2020'

b'Innovating for a better future. \n\nDhruva is taking steps to make electric energy more accessible for others. Rachel wants to protect her county\xe2\x80\x99s trees from an invasive predator. b'Every individual has unique talents and gifts that, when unlocked and maximized, can create a better world. \n\nHear from CEO Charles Koch and our employees as they share their personal journeys to self-actualization.'

b"Meet our employees giving legal assistance to those who need it most.

For some Americans, one criminal misstep in life can cascade into an endless stream of trouble \xe2\x80\x94 getting a job, affording a home and even supporting a family. It's why we're leading a pro bono initiative, helping people get free legal help to overcome personal barriers to reach their full potential. 

Read about the employees across Koch companies driving our pro bono efforts \xe2\x80\x93 link in bio."

b'Creating value and helping people improve their lives is core to our vision \xe2\x80\x93 and we use a long term business philosophy to help bring that vision to life.\n\nLearn more about the heart of how we work.'
b'A self-actualized workforce. A real solution.'

b'Turning boxes into boxes into boxes.\n\nEvery year, our team at @georgiapacific collects almost 5 million tons of recovered paper products\xe2\x80\xaffrom large retailers, grocery stores, and residences for recycling. These boxes keep your deliveries coming. Learn how \xe2\x80\x93 link in bio.'

b'Building the bridge to a better life. 

The state of Georgia handed Gwen Boyd-Willis a four-month sentence for a petty crime. But her record became a 15-year burden as she tried unsuccessfully to put her multiple college degrees to work. Then Michael Davis, a lawyer on our team at @georgiapacific working with the @gajusticeproject, took her case. Michael volunteered his time as part of our companywide pro bono initiative to break down barriers and expand justice opportunities to help every person reach their full potential. Now, Gwen Boyd-Willis is finally free from the stigma of a criminal record. 

Link in bio to read her story.'

b'"Simply being the best in the world at what you do isn\xe2\x80\x99t good enough." b'Our director of environment, health & safety, Sheryl Corrigan, shares her personal story of realizing her true potential. b'Efficient logistics are truckers\xe2\x80\x99 best hope of getting home on time to be with their families.\n\nOne man who understands the importance of efficiency and stability is Wallace Nelson, the shipping lead on our team at @georgiapacific, who interacts with dozens of truck drivers a day. Completed orders, efficient equipment, smart route-planning, and fewer deadhead hours are the ways that lead to hyper-efficient logistics. Read more about how Georgia-Pacific and KBX Logistics use software to lead to more efficiently - Link in bio.'
